Good responses all... Now I'm going to "refine" my questions a little bit, and throw in my answers. What I was trying to get at is this - imagine that you are a Christian who is a citizen of some other country than the United States. LOTS of things that the next president will affect WON'T affect you... taxes, for instance. The size of government. But, foreign policy will. And you also care about the poor, the widow, the orphan, the innocent child. So you want to vote in their interest. 

I recently read a book called "Jesus For President," which has two main points. First of all, that the idea that there is one candidate who is "God's candidate" for the White House is a lie from Hell. The second point is that this idea, in a way, calls us to place our heavenly citizenship subordinate to our earthly citizenship. If my voting one way can bring about greater good for my neighbor and my enemy, even if it is at my expense, then I should vote that way.

