So here are my thoughts on the question.

1. Why should a Christian vote for McCain/Palin? 

McCain knows that American needs to scale down the war in Iraq, but he has not blindly committed to a "pull-out" date which could result in situation like we have in Afghanistan - where our former allies (Bin Laden) become our enemies because we stop caring about them. His policies here could potentially be better for Iraqis than Obama's

McCain believes, as I do, and as I feel scripture teaches, that life begins at conception. This should affect how he decides policy on abortion. 

McCain is a strong believer in the integrity of the family. Policy decisions should reflect this belief, for the benefit of the institution of the family in America.

2. Why should a Christian vote for Obama/Biden?

Obama has stated that while he is pro-choice, he longs for a world where abortion does not exist. In this effort, he worked with the Democratic party to add a statement to the party platform calling for abortion reduction. Studies have shown that Democratic economic policies (child support, family planning education, unemployment for pregnant women, etc) has a significant (up to 30%) effect on the abortion rate. Republican legal policies (parental notification or permission) have a negligible effect on the abortion rate. Furthermore, as with gay marriage, abortion is now a state-level issue. So, while nation-wide economic policy has great potential to lower the abortion rate, nation-wide legal policy cannot, because it is not a federal-level issue.

While Obama's position on the war in Iraq may result in problems, his foreign policy generally calls for less military intervention and more foreign aid. The fact that America believes itself to be a Christian nation (85% of the population calling themselves Christian) is undeniable, and the world believes this as well. Obama's foreign policy would be more "friendly" and more popular worldwide. Christianity's reputation has been tarnished by the actions of our "Christian" president. Both of the current candidates claim to be Christian, and I feel that Obama's foreign policy would look and feel more Christian to the rest of the world (though personally I don't think the commander-in-chief of any military can actually be Christian, but that is a thought for another page).

Yes, it is the church's responsibility to care for the poor and the sick. Is the church doing this? What if the church voted in a government which cared for the poor and the sick?

We are called to be stewards of the environment. Obama's policies make this a more clear priority than McCain's do.

In closing, let me state that because I don't believe God has "a man for the white house," I really don't "like" either of these candidates. There has only ever been one government which God approved of - Israel's theocracy. If I were to write someone in on the ballot, I'd write in "God." (Maybe YHWH to make sure there was no confusion. I should learn to write that in Hebrew.)

